    <field name="scopecontent_teim">Written from Fort Monroe, VA, these letters date from the period of Vanderhoef's first enlistment at the age of 16 as a musician with Co. B, 1st Artillery. Mainly consisting of inquiries after the health of various family members and protestations of eternal friendship, they nevertheless provide moments of interest. He thinks he might have his photograph taken; the soldiers must collect rainwater in barrels, for every well they sink is salty, and he now likes this rainwater "better than Croton water." Fishing for striped bass provides good sport; and in one letter (Dec 20th 1855) Vanderhoef bursts with indignation, having heard that his father is homeless and penniless and no one in the family has taken him in.</field>
